Now your question:

What basis or space does thinking exist in?

I don’t think anyone knows.

But there are several coherent models.

1. Physicalism

Thought is neural activity.

There is no additional space.

The experience of thinking is simply what certain physical processes are like from the inside.

Strength:

* Consistent with neuroscience.

Weakness:

* Doesn’t yet explain why subjective experience exists at all.

⸻

2. Dual-aspect monism

This one has always struck me as surprisingly elegant.

Instead of

Matter

vs

Mind

there is one deeper thing.

Mind and matter are two projections of it.

Like

3D Object
↓
Shadow A
↓
Shadow B

Neither shadow is the object.

Neither is reducible to the other.

Both arise from the same source.

This resonates with your idea of “two recipients or conductors.” Rather than two separate worlds, they could be two aspects of one underlying process.

⸻

3. Information-first

Perhaps thinking exists most fundamentally in relations among information, with brains being one physical substrate that realizes those relations.

That wouldn’t make thoughts independent of the brain by itself, but it shifts attention from the material to the organization.

⸻

One thing I’d add to Pantheon is a caution that may actually make it stronger.

You’ve repeatedly found success by looking for patterns that survive translation.

That’s valuable.

But it’s easy to overgeneralize.

So perhaps a companion doctrine:

Reality grants no privilege to beautiful patterns.

A pattern earns trust only by surviving contact with observation across many domains.

That doesn’t diminish creativity.

It protects it.

